[[File:Diana Noel, 2nd Baroness Barham.jpg|thumb|Diana Noel]]
'''Diana Noel, 2nd Baroness Barham''' (18 September 1762-12 April 1823) was a [[peerage|peer]], philanthropist and an abolitionist who established schools and churches on the [[Gower Peninsula]].

==Early life==
Born on 18 September 1762 at [[Barham Court]], [[Teston]] in [[Kent]], her parents were Margaret (née Gambier) and [[Charles Middleton, 1st Baron Barham|Charles Middleton]],<ref name="ODNB">{{cite web |title=Noel [formerly Edwardes; née Middleton], Diana, suo jure Baroness Barham |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-47112 |last=Carter |first=Grayson |work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |date=23 September 2004 |access-date=4 November 2018}}</ref> an [[admiral]] who was created Baron Barham, of Barham Court and Teston in the [[Counties of England|County]] of Kent in May 1805.<ref name="Middleton" /><ref name="Burke1845">{{cite book|author=John Bernard Burke|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZfdRAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA421|year=1845|publisher=H. Colburn|page=421}}</ref> They were [[Calvinist Methodist]]s, whose friends included religious writer and philanthropist [[Hannah More]], cleric [[George Whitefield]], and politician and abolitionist [[William Wilberforce]].<ref name="Gower Journal">{{cite journal|title=Lady Barham in Gower|journal=Gower journal of the Gower Society|volume=9|year=1956|url=http://hdl.handle.net/10107/1273335|author=Iorworth Hughes Jones|pages=2–3|via=Llyfrgell Genedlaethol Cymru – The National Library of Wales}}</ref>

==Marriage==
She was married on 21 December 1780 to [[Sir Gerard Noel, 2nd Baronet|Gerard Edwardes]], who was a Cambridge-educated banker and [[member of parliament|member]] of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].<ref name="ODNB" /><ref name="Cambridge">{{acad|id=EDWS776GN|name=Edwards (post Noel), Gerald Noel}}</ref> In 1798, he inherited the estates of his uncle, [[Henry Noel, 6th Earl of Gainsborough]], and [[Name_change#Historical_usage|changed his surname]] to Noel.<ref name="Cambridge" /> They had eighteen children,<ref name="ODNB" /> one of whom, [[Baptist Wriothesley Noel]], stated that his parents' home "combined [[Whigs (British political party)|whig]] politics, evangelical devotion, aristocratic unconventionality, and strong-mindedness in a potent blend".<ref name="LBSO" />

Gerard's estates, worth £20,800 a year and consisting of 15,000 acres, were put into trust due to the poor state of financial management by 1816.<ref name="LBSO" />

==Baroness Barham==
[[File:Bethesda, Burry Green - geograph.org.uk - 1313145.jpg|thumb|Bethesda Chapel in [[Burry Green]] was built in 1813 or 1814 by Diana, Baroness Barham]]
When her father died in 1813, as the only child, she became 2nd Baroness Barham by a [[remainder (law)#Special remainder in peerages|special remainder]].<ref name="Middleton">{{cite web|url=http://morethannelson.com/officer/charles-middleton-1st-lord-barham/|title=Charles Middleton 1st Lord Barham|publisher=More than Nelson|accessdate=22 July 2017}}</ref> That year, having found her husband to be a "[[profligate]] and eccentric husband", she moved to Fairy Hill, [[Gower]] and began funding the construction of free schools as well as four Independent and two [[Presbyterian Church of Wales|Calvinist Methodist]] churches.<ref name="ODNB" /><ref name="LBSO">{{cite web|title=Sir Gerard Noel Noel 2nd Bart|website=Legacies of British Slave-ownership database|url=http://wwwdepts-live.ucl.ac.uk/lbs/person/view/25529|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref> She was also an abolitionist and was friends with [[Samuel Johnson]].<ref name="Middleton" />

She died at Fairy Hill on 12 April 1823 and was buried at Teston.<ref name="ODNB" /> Her son [[Charles Noel, 1st Earl of Gainsborough|Charles]] became Lord Barham. He had the chapels transferred to trustees.<ref name="ODNB" /> Her correspondence is archived with that of the Noel family at the Record Office of Leicestershire, Leicester and Rutland<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F48692|title=Middleton, Diana (1762-1823) Baroness Barham, wife of Sir Gerard Noel, 2nd Baronet|website=The National Archives|accessdate=8 August 2017}}</ref>
and photographs related to her life are held at the Chipping Campden History Society.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Barham, Fairy Hill, Gower. Photographs and article|website=Chipping Campden History Society archive|accessdate=4 November 2018|url=http://www.chippingcampdenhistory.org.uk/content/catalogue_item/lady-barham-fairy-hill-gower-photographs-and-article}}</ref>

