{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox member of the Knesset | image = File:Yaakov Asher cropped.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1965|7|2|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Ramat Gan]], [[Israel]] | death_date = | Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 2013|19]], [[Israeli legislative election, 2015|20]] | party1 = [[United Torah Judaism]] | partyyears1 = 2013–2015 | party2 = [[United Torah Judaism]] | partyyears2 = 2016– }} '''Ya'akov Asher''' ({{lang-he-n|יַעֲקֹב אָשֵׁר}}; born 2 July 1965) is an [[Israel]]i rabbi and politician who currently serves as a member of the Knesset for the [[United Torah Judaism]] alliance. A member of the [[Degel HaTorah]] party, he previously served as a member of the Knesset between 2013 and 2015, and was also the thirteenth mayor of [[Bnei Brak]], having taken office in 2008.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1058788.html No walk in the park in Bnei Brak - yet] Haaretz, 26 January 2009</ref>
==Biography== Ya'akov Asher was born and raised in [[Ramat Gan]]. He served in the [[Israel Defense Forces]]. Asher is married, with seven children.<ref name=JP>[http://www.jpost.com/Features/InThespotlight/Article.aspx?id=302725 Meet the MK: Ya'acov Asher] The Jerusalem Post, 10 February 2013</ref>
==Political career== Asher ran for mayor of [[El'ad]], but lost to Tzuriel Krispel. He became mayor of Bnei Brak in 2008, after 19 years on the city council.<ref>[http://www.mynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-3625657,00.html Ya'akov Asher promises "not to ask for 100 days of grace"] MyNet, 23 November 2008 {{he icon}}</ref> He became mayor without an election in the wake of an agreement between Degel HaTorah and [[Agudat Yisrael]] to share the post of mayor on an alternating basis.
Prior to the [[Israeli legislative election, 2013|2013 Knesset elections]], he was placed seventh on the United Torah Judaism list, and entered the Knesset as the alliance won seven seats. His election to the Knesset meant he had to resign his mayoral position. He was placed seventh on the UTJ list again for the [[Israeli legislative election, 2015|2015 elections]],<ref>[http://www.bechirot20.gov.il/election/Candidates/Pages/OneListCandidates.aspx?LPF=Search&WebId=6adadc15-e476-480b-9746-04490aedeb0f&ListID=ba72a662-765c-45af-9d48-fb68080956af&ItemID=44&FieldID=ListNickname_GxS_Text United Torah Judaism list] Central Elections Committee</ref> but lost his seat when the alliance was reduced to six seats. However, he re-entered the Knesset in May 2016 as a replacement for [[Meir Porush]], when he stood down as part of a seat rotation agreement between the parties in United Torah Judaism.<ref>[http://matzav.com/meir-porush-resigns-yaakov-asher-to-fill-his-knesset-seat/ Meir Porush Resigns, Yaakov Asher to Fill His Knesset Seat] Matzav, 22 May 2016</ref>
